# Git Commit Standards

Git history is extremely important. Follow these rules for all commits.

## Hard Requirements

- Do: keep commits small and logically atomic.
- Do: use imperative subject line, <= 50 chars, no trailing period.
- Do: include body explaining what/why for non-trivial changes.
- Do not: mix unrelated concerns in one commit.
- Why: clean history improves debugging, review quality, and rollback safety.

## Opinionated Defaults

- Wrap body lines around 72 chars.
- Separate subject/body with a blank line.
- Reference issue IDs when available.

## Exceptions

- Tiny typo/docs-only fixes may omit body if intent is obvious.
- Emergency fixes can use short messages if follow-up cleanup commit is planned.

## Acceptance Checks

- Commit messages follow formatting and intent rules.
- Each commit maps to one logical change area.
- Reviewers can infer rationale from subject/body alone.

## Commit Message Template

```bash
# If applied, this commit will...

# Why is this change needed?

# How does it address the issue?

# Provide links to any relevant tickets, articles or other resources
```

## Examples

```bash
✅ GOOD
Add authentication endpoint

Implement token-based authentication to secure API access.

Uses short-lived access credentials with secure refresh handling.
Improves session security while keeping client retry behavior predictable.

Related: #123
```

```bash
❌ BAD
fix stuff

Fixed the bug
```
